          "title": "The intercession — where Moses teaches Israel to stand (vv. 25-29)",
          "body": "Moses closes the chapter by reproducing the content of his forty-day intercession, and in doing so he gives Israel a theology of prayer under divine judgment. The prayer contains not a single word about Israel's merit, future resolve, or spiritual performance. Its entire argumentative weight falls on four grounds: (1) divine ownership — 'Your people, even Your inheritance' (v.26); (2) past redemptive act — 'whom You have redeemed through Your greatness, whom You have brought out of Egypt with a mighty hand' (v.26); (3) the patriarchal covenant — 'Remember Your servants, Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob' (v.27); (4) God's international reputation — 'lest the land from which You brought us say... the LORD was not able to bring them into the land' (v.28). Calvin notes on this passage that Moses does not plead Israel's worthiness but 'transfers the cause from the people to God Himself, who would suffer reproach if He destroyed those whom He had openly declared to be His.' The prayer is the enacted application of the chapter's thesis: since the people have no righteousness to appeal to, the intercessor appeals to God's covenant, God's power, and God's name. The New Testament's greater Mediator makes the same move in John 17 and in His ongoing high-priestly intercession (Hebrews 7:25)."
