          "body": "Deuteronomy 9 is one of the Old Testament's most decisive texts against the idea that Israel's covenant relationship was grounded in national moral achievement. Paul's argument in Romans 9-11 — that God's election of Israel was never based on merit — has its primary Old Testament support here and in Deuteronomy 7:6-8 ('not because you were more in number... but because the LORD loved you and kept the oath'). The chapter's threefold 'not because of your righteousness' (vv.4-6) is the hermeneutical key: the land-gift is grace. The dispossession of the Canaanites is divine judgment on their wickedness; it is not divine reward for Israel's holiness. Tim Keller has pressed this point in his exposition of Deuteronomy: the chapter is not primarily about ancient Israel's specific failures but about a structural truth — God's people have always received more than they have earned, have always required a mediator they could not supply themselves, and have always been maintained by a faithfulness that runs from the patriarchal promises forward. The forty-day intercessions of Moses point beyond themselves to the perfect intercession of the One who stands in the gap not merely by fasting prayer but by bearing in His own body the wrath that would have destroyed the people (Romans 8:34; Hebrews 9:24)."
